{"title_page": "Jacqueline Novak", "text_new": "'''Jacqueline Novak''' (born Sept. 3, 1982) is an American stand-up comedian, actor, writer, and published author.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2728665/</ref><ref>https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public</ref> Her Off-Broadway, one-woman show, ''Get On Your Knees'' is a [[New York Times]] \u201cCritic\u2019s Pick.\u201d<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/theater/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees-review.html</ref> Her performance in this show has been nominated for a 2020 [[Drama Desk Award]] for Outstanding Solo Performance<ref>https://www.dramadeskawards.com/nominees/</ref>. Novak's memoir ''How to Weep in Public: Feeble Offerings on Depression from One Who Knows'' was published by [[Crown]] in 2016.<ref>https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public.</ref>\n== Early Life==\nNovak was born in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]], the daughter of Gregory Novak, a retired marketing executive, and Naomi (Wall) Novak.<ref>Acknowledgements, ''How to Weep in Public: Feeble Offerings on Depression from One Who Knows'', Jacqueline Novak (Crown, 2016). https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public </ref> She is the youngest of three children.<ref>Acknowledgements, ''How to Weep in Public: Feeble Offerings on Depression from One Who Knows'', Jacqueline Novak (Crown, 2016). https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public </ref> The family moved to [[Chappaqua, New York]] when she was two years old.<ref>https://patch.com/new-york/chappaqua/calendar/event/20160909/13799/chappaqua-library-author-talk-how-to-weep-in-public-feeble-offerings-on-depression-from-one-who-know</ref> She attended [[Horace Greeley High School]] there and then went on to [[Georgetown University]].<ref>https://www.talkinbroadway.com/allthatchat_new/d.php?id=2476677</ref> Novak and [[John Mulaney]] were in same college improv troupe at Georgetown, both cast by [[Nick Kroll]], who himself was cast in that troupe a couple of years earlier by [[Mike Birbiglia]].<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/04/theater/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees.html</ref> \n\n== Career==\nAfter graduation college, Novak began doing stand-up in the downtown New York City comedy scene, often hosting shows with comic/actor [[John Early (comedian)|John Early]].<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/07/jacqueline-novak-john-early-get-on-your-knees-interview.html</ref> During this time she wrote her memoir ''How to Weep in Public''.<ref>https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public</ref> She put her efforts next on developing a one-person show, which eventually became the hit Off-Broadway performance ''Get On Your Knees''.<ref>\"https://www.vulture.com/2019/07/jacqueline-novak-john-early-get-on-your-knees-interview.html</ref>\n\nNovak has appeared on \"[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]\" and as well as \u201c[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]\".<ref>\u201dhttps://www.imdb.com/name/nm2728665/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm</ref> She has also been on \"[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]],\u201d<ref>https://www.crfashionbook.com/culture/a28468957/jacqueline-novak-john-early-comics-theatre/</ref> [[HBO]]'s \u201c[[2 Dope Queens]],\"<ref>\u201dhttps://www.imdb.com/name/nm2728665/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm</ref> \"[[Watch What Happens Live with Andy Cohen]],\"<ref>http://apeconcerts.com/attraction/jacqueline-novak/</ref> and has had her own half-hour stand-up special on [[Comedy Central]]'s \"The Half Hour.''\"<ref>\u201dhttp://www.cc.com/episodes/p78vfh/the-half-hour-jacqueline-novak-season-5-ep-512</ref> \n\nHer TV credits include appearances on \"[[Inside Amy Schumer]],\" \"[[Animals]]\" (HBO), and \"The Characters\" ([[Netflix]]).<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> She has also written for \"[[Broad City]],\" \"Good Talk With [[Anthony Jeselnik]]\" (Comedy Central), and \"[[Soft Focus with Jena Friedman]]\" ([[Adult Swim]]).<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref>\n\n=== ''Get On Your Knees'' ===\n''Get On Your Knees'' began as a one-woman show Novak presented at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in Scotland in 2018.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees-encounter.html</ref> At the time the show was called ''How Embarrassing for Her''.<ref>\u201dhttps://www.fest-mag.com/edinburgh/comedy/jacqueline-novak-how-embarrassing-for-her</ref> After the festival, she workshopped it in Los Angeles.<ref>https://www.dynastytypewriter.com/calendar/jacqnovakjune2</ref> Mike Birbiglia and [[Natasha Lyonne]] saw the show, and Birbiglia decided to produce it for a six-week Off-Broadway run at the [[Cherry Lane Theatre]] in Manhattan's [[West Village]].<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> Lyonne agreed to present it.<ref>https://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/jacqueline-novak-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-cherry-lane-theater</ref><ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> John Early was chosen as director.<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> Due to its popularity, the run at Cherry Lane was extended, then moved to the larger Off-Broadway [[Lucille Lortel Theatre]], also in the West Village.<ref>https://www.playbill.com/article/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees-extends-again-off-broadway</ref> Recognized on two New York Times lists, \u201cBest Theater of 2019\u201d<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/03/arts/best-broadway-theater-show.html</ref> and \u201cBest Comedy of 2019\u201d<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/17/arts/television/best-comedy.html</ref>, the show was extended several more times.<ref>https://www.playbill.com/article/jacqueline-novaks-get-on-your-knees-extends-again-off-broadway</ref>\n\nA U.S. and international tour of the show is scheduled in 2020.<ref>https://www.playbill.com/article/jacqueline-novaks-hit-solo-show-get-on-your-knees-to-tour-us-and-england</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jokesnovak.com/ Jacqueline Novak Official Site]\n* {{IMDb name | nm2728665 }}\n\n\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jacqueline Novak''' (born Sept. 3, 1982) is an American stand-up comedian, actor, writer, and published author.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2728665/</ref><ref>https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public</ref> Her Off-Broadway, one-woman show, ''Get On Your Knees'' is a [[New York Times]] \u201cCritic\u2019s Pick.\u201d<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/22/theater/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees-review.html</ref> Novak's memoir ''How to Weep in Public: Feeble Offerings on Depression from One Who Knows'' was published by [[Crown]] in 2016.<ref>https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public.</ref>\n== Early Life==\nNovak was born in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]], the daughter of Gregory Novak, a retired marketing executive, and Naomi (Wall) Novak.<ref>Acknowledgements, ''How to Weep in Public: Feeble Offerings on Depression from One Who Knows'', Jacqueline Novak (Crown, 2016). https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public </ref> She is the youngest of three children.<ref>Acknowledgements, ''How to Weep in Public: Feeble Offerings on Depression from One Who Knows'', Jacqueline Novak (Crown, 2016). https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public </ref> The family moved to [[Chappaqua, New York]] when she was two years old.<ref>https://patch.com/new-york/chappaqua/calendar/event/20160909/13799/chappaqua-library-author-talk-how-to-weep-in-public-feeble-offerings-on-depression-from-one-who-know</ref> She attended [[Horace Greeley High School]] there and then went on to [[Georgetown University]].<ref>https://www.talkinbroadway.com/allthatchat_new/d.php?id=2476677</ref> Novak and [[John Mulaney]] were in same college improv troupe at Georgetown, both cast by [[Nick Kroll]], who himself was cast in that troupe a couple of years earlier by [[Mike Birbiglia]].<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/04/theater/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees.html</ref> \n\n== Career==\nAfter graduation college, Novak began doing stand-up in the downtown New York City comedy scene, often hosting shows with comic/actor [[John Early (comedian)|John Early]].<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/07/jacqueline-novak-john-early-get-on-your-knees-interview.html</ref> During this time she wrote her memoir ''How to Weep in Public''.<ref>https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/22125249-how-to-weep-in-public</ref> She put her efforts next on developing a one-person show, which eventually became the hit Off-Broadway performance ''Get On Your Knees''.<ref>\"https://www.vulture.com/2019/07/jacqueline-novak-john-early-get-on-your-knees-interview.html</ref>\n\nNovak has appeared on \"[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]\" and as well as \u201c[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]\".<ref>\u201dhttps://www.imdb.com/name/nm2728665/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm</ref> She has also been on \"[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]],\u201d<ref>https://www.crfashionbook.com/culture/a28468957/jacqueline-novak-john-early-comics-theatre/</ref> [[HBO]]'s \u201c[[2 Dope Queens]],\"<ref>\u201dhttps://www.imdb.com/name/nm2728665/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm</ref> \"[[Watch What Happens Live with Andy Cohen]],\"<ref>http://apeconcerts.com/attraction/jacqueline-novak/</ref> and has had her own half-hour stand-up special on [[Comedy Central]]'s \"The Half Hour.''\"<ref>\u201dhttp://www.cc.com/episodes/p78vfh/the-half-hour-jacqueline-novak-season-5-ep-512</ref> \n\nHer TV credits include appearances on \"[[Inside Amy Schumer]],\" \"[[Animals]]\" (HBO), and \"The Characters\" ([[Netflix]]).<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> She has also written for \"[[Broad City]],\" \"Good Talk With [[Anthony Jeselnik]]\" (Comedy Central), and \"[[Soft Focus with Jena Friedman]]\" ([[Adult Swim]]).<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref>\n\n=== ''Get On Your Knees'' ===\n''Get On Your Knees'' began as a one-woman show Novak presented at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in Scotland in 2018.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees-encounter.html</ref> At the time the show was called ''How Embarrassing for Her''.<ref>\u201dhttps://www.fest-mag.com/edinburgh/comedy/jacqueline-novak-how-embarrassing-for-her</ref> After the festival, she workshopped it in Los Angeles.<ref>https://www.dynastytypewriter.com/calendar/jacqnovakjune2</ref> Mike Birbiglia and [[Natasha Lyonne]] saw the show, and Birbiglia decided to produce it for a six-week Off-Broadway run at the [[Cherry Lane Theatre]] in Manhattan's [[West Village]].<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> Lyonne agreed to present it.<ref>https://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/jacqueline-novak-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-cherry-lane-theater</ref><ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> John Early was chosen as director.<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/05/jacqueline-novak-comedian-off-broadway-debut-mike-birbiglia-natasha-lyonne-get-on-your-knees-1202623508/</ref> Due to its popularity, the run at Cherry Lane was extended, then moved to the larger Off-Broadway [[Lucille Lortel Theatre]], also in the West Village.<ref>https://www.playbill.com/article/jacqueline-novak-get-on-your-knees-extends-again-off-broadway</ref> Recognized on two New York Times lists, \u201cBest Theater of 2019\u201d<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/03/arts/best-broadway-theater-show.html</ref> and \u201cBest Comedy of 2019\u201d<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/17/arts/television/best-comedy.html</ref>, the show was extended several more times.<ref>https://www.playbill.com/article/jacqueline-novaks-get-on-your-knees-extends-again-off-broadway</ref>\n\nA U.S. and international tour of the show is scheduled in 2020.<ref>https://www.playbill.com/article/jacqueline-novaks-hit-solo-show-get-on-your-knees-to-tour-us-and-england</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jokesnovak.com/ Jacqueline Novak Official Site]\n* {{IMDb name | nm2728665 }}\n\n\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "123BigCheese", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added nomination for 2020 Drama Desk Award.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacqueline_Novak"}
{"title_page": "Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Historical Record Survey", "text_new": "The 1934-1936 '''Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Historical Record Survey''' (also called \"cards\") was an early demographic review of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the  United States]] and Canada. The backgrounds of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were later studied in a number of ways - racial and ethnic heritage, previous religious background, geographical spread and sometimes how these have changed over the years. Complimentary data sources have also been used to add to some of the reviews including US Census publications and Bah\u00e1'\u00ed directories published in periodicals of [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed literature]]. \n\nA couple of these studies look specifically at the burgeoning black population of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds amidst the wider society practice of continuing [[Racial_segregation_in_the_United_States#New_Deal_era|era of social segregation in the American society of the time]] which was against the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed teaching of the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith and the unity of humanity|unity of all humanity]]. The vast majority of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were white and mostly elder women, but the black segment of those states Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were in responded more to the religion than the white population of those states did. The religion was also initially attracting Protestants, especially Unitarian Universalists and also among other more mainstream liberal denominations, but as history approached 1936 and beyond it attracted a greater diversity of religious backgrounds as it continued to grow more by conversion than by migration. However intentional migration had been undertaken shortly after this time - the religion had only been present in a few states mostly in the Northeast to North Central and West Coast coming up to 1936 but a goal was set to spread the religion to every state by 1944. As it spread inward from the West coast this mere presence established recognizable proportional membership in the population while in the higher population of the South it did not. But there it did take root too, more so among the black communities along the coastal regions of the South. Indeed this wave of activity was undertaken during the first Seven Year Plan established by [[Shoghi Effendi]] which had the intranational goal of establishing a community in every state as well as establishing the religion in the countries of Latin America.\n\n==Development, context, and reviews of the Survey==\nThe 1934 American national convention affirmed the request of the national race amity committee for a survey of the racial makeup of the community affirming the request of the national amity committee work asking for localized amity committees and consolidation with concerned groups like the NAACP and Urban League.<ref name=GreenThesis>{{cite thesis |author=Jerome Green|date=2004 |title=Trial and Triumph: The Origins of the Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Faith in Black America |type=Senior Fellowship Thesis|publisher=Dartmouth College |oclc= 242842724 |url=http://bahai-library.com/green_bahai_black_america |access-date=Feb 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|p36}} The same year the national youth committee including [[Marion Holley]] recommended a census be taken of youth as well.<ref>{{cite magazine | title =Youth committee | magazine = Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed News | pages = 23\u20134 | date = May 1934|issue= 74 | url = http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=01&page=601 | access-date =Dec 29, 2017}}</ref> The Survey developed included historical information of the respondent - the date and place they were born, the date and place they joined the religion, and where they were living at the time of the Survey as well as their national and religious background.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p66}}\n\nThe Survey was widespread by the summer of 1935.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p37}} The complete collection of respondents is a little unclear. There have been four reviews of the Survey: \n* In 1980 Arthur Hampson did a geography PhD using the Survey as one of his main sources of information to review the development of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community using more demographic information.<ref name=HampsonPhD>{{cite thesis |last=Hampson |first=Arthur |date=May 1980 |title= The growth and spread of the Baha'i Faith |type=PhD |publisher=Department of Geography, University of Hawaii |id= UMI 8022655|oclc=652914306 |url= https://bahai-library.com/hampson_growth_spread_bahai|access-date=Feb 10, 2020}}</ref> \n* In 1982 Gayle Morrison included an analysis of the black community from the 1936 Survey in her biography of Hand of the Cause [[Louis G. Gregory]].<ref name=Morrison>{{cite book|author=Gayle Morrison|title=To Move the World: Louis G. Gregory and the Advancement of Racial Unity in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tl8wAAAAYAAJ |date=1 January 1982|publisher=Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Pub. Trust|isbn=978-0-87743-171-8|oclc= 988271963|pages=203-9}}</ref>\n* In 1982 Peter Smith used the Survey via a selection of every third respondent<ref name=SmithStudiesv1>{{cite book\n | author= Peter Smith\n | author-link = Peter Smith\n | title =Studies in Babi and Baha\u02bci History |chapter=The American Baha\u02bci community, 1894-1917: A preliminary survey\n | publisher =Kalimat Press\n | volume =1 |editor= [[Moojan Momen]]\n | date =1982\n | location =Los Angeles\n | oclc= 863423149\n | isbn =9780933770164}}</ref>{{rp|p118}} to review the religion and examined the depth of religious backgrounds that could be perceived in anecdotes of the backgrounds of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by then. Smith did a second review of the data published in 2004 mostly looking at comparisons with other surveys in other times and places.<ref name=BFitW-Smith>{{cite book|author=Peter Smith|editor=Peter Smith |series=Studies in the B\u00e1b\u00ed and Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Religions|volume=14|editor2=Anthony L. Lee |title=Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the West|chapter=The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the West: A Survey|pages=3-60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x7wyJdyE60oC|year=2004|publisher=Kalimat Press|isbn=978-1-890688-11-0}}</ref>\n* Robert Stockman included a review of the Survey especially for members of three communities in his PhD in 1990 including transcribing all of the physical cards into a computer file.<ref name=StockmanThD>{{cite thesis |last=Stockman |first=Robert H. |date=January 1990 |title=The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith and American Protestantism |type= ThD |publisher= Harvard Divinity School |oclc= 23934626 |pages=43-58 |url= |access-date=}}</ref>\n* In 2004 Gerome Green finished a senior thesis at Dartmouth College also reviewing the Survey for a look at the black community.<ref name=GreenThesis/> \nHampson counted 1784 respondents<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p323}} of which 1729 were from the United States proper.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p320}} Morrison and Stockman counted 1813 by 1936-7.<ref name=Morrison/><ref name=StockmanThD/> Smith's sample approach would have totaled about 1803.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p118}} Stockman collected the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed population up to about 1936 finding about 4000 people had joined the religion up to then.<ref name=stockmanv25n3>{{cite journal\n | last =Stockman\n | first =Robert \n | author-link =Robert Stockman\n | title = The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in America: one hundred years\n | journal =World Order\n | volume =25\n | issue =3 |editor1= Firuz Kazemzadeh |editor2= Betty J. Fisher |editor3= Howard Garey |editor4= Robert H. Stockman |editor5= James D. Stokes\n | pages =9-23\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the United States\n | date =1994\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:World_Order2_Vol25_Issue3.pdf&page=11\n | issn = 0043-8804\n | access-date = Feb 14, 2020}}</ref> Unasked for, but some respondents included multi-page autobiographies.<ref name=StockmanThD/>\n\nHampson was able to compare the community Survey with the Census of Religions of the United States for 1936 and early dates<ref name=1936FedCensus>For similar information see US Federal Census referenced the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community in summery for 1936 and briefly of earlier dates: {{cite book|title=Census of Religious Bodies, 1936: Bulletin No. 1 of 78 |volume=2|number=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4gBJZuh2RhAC |chapter=Baha\u2019is| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4gBJZuh2RhAC&pg=PA76 |year=1941|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=76\u201382}}</ref> which counted 2584 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the continental US in 1936. The census information was gathered from the respective religious communities - no additional censuses were done.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p137}} So the national assembly's survey represented about 70% of the community of the US and Canada as understood by the national assembly. Still the Survey had the lowest percentage of responses in New York(mostly the city) and Illinois(mostly Chicago) and highest in the whole West.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p321}}\n\n==The overall community ==\nStockman estimated, partly on the basis of the Survey, that roughly 50-100 people identified as Bah\u00e1'\u00eds during the time 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 was in America in 1912.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert H. Stockman|author-link=Robert H. Stockman|title=\u02bbAbdu\u02bcl-Bah\u00e1 in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0enOpwAACAAJ|year=2012|publisher=Baha'i Pub.|isbn=978-1-931847-97-1|pages=362-3}}</ref>\n\nSmith broke down the respondents who were Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by 1919, a total of 197 individuals still alive and members of the community by 1936: 90% were northern European (British, German, Scandinavian, generally \u201cwhite\u201d without ethnic background specified,) 6% African-American, but absent any Southern or Eastern European and Irish.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp118-9}}<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p47}} This population was previously 33% of mainstream Protestant Christian background (Episcopal, Methodist, Congregationalist, Presbyterian and Baptist,) 11% Lutheran, 5% Unitarian/Universalist, followed distantly at 3% by metaphysical denominations (Swedenborgian, Christian Science, Theosophy and New Thought,) while a definite if small overall presence was of those raised in Bah\u00e1'\u00ed homes.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp119-20}} Or, put another way by Smith in 2004: 56% Protestant of any stripe, 17% \"Christian\", 5% Catholic, 2-3% Jewish, and 4-5% Bah\u00e1'\u00ed.<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p49}} The overall pattern of a few percent raised Bah\u00e1'\u00ed was shown to be the case in a number of other surveys, (outside the Persian community in the West that arrived later.)<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p49}} It was also 66% women.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p121}}\n\nStockman broke down the communities of New York city, Chicago, and Kenosha, and across time, for what details they provided. Those three communities were significantly different:<ref name=StockmanThD/> Kenosha was mostly Scandinavians and Germans, with mostly early converts being 1st generation immigrants, Chicago started with half American followed by English and German and added a significant black proportion of the community after 1921, and in New York the community identified as mostly American then English, and then added a proportion of German. His analysis also showed broadly similar patterns in the communities of Christian or Protestant groups which started out a dominant group and dropped percentage-wise approaching 1936 while those raised as Bah\u00e1'\u00eds kept increasing with a couple small groups non-Protestants, (Catholics, Jews, or metaphysical groups) adding in as well: it started out more Protestant than the US in general but became more diverse than the US in general.<ref name=StockmanThD/>\n\nHampson analyzed the Survey and Census results relative to the states that had a Bah\u00e1'\u00ed population, a minority of the states mostly in the upper mid-West to the Northeast and California, and compared the racial and religious groups for just those states. He argued that the rate of black declarants in those states was much higher than being proportional to the black population of those states, indeed their rate of affiliation with the religion was above that of the rate of white presence in those states,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp333-5}} and, though fewer of the Survey respondents were sufficiently particular about their religious background, agreed they were mostly from a Protestant background with the refinement that the contribution of the Unitarians was well above that of their proportion of their presence in those states and above that of all other protestant denominations though Episcopalian and Congregational were nearly tied for a distant second.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp338-342}} The lowest rate of religious backgrounds relative to their population in the states with significant Bah\u00e1'\u00eds presence were those of Jewish and Catholic backgrounds.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p340}} However Stockman characterizes these groups as contributing significantly to the religious diversity of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community,<ref name=stockmanv25n3/> and Smith also that in other surveys at other times Jews showed a significantly higher percentage of some communities.<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|pp49-50}}\n\nHampson was able to do a county-by-county analysis including of earlier times.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p274}} By 1919 most Bah\u00e1'\u00ed communities had less than two dozen adults and many were an isolated group or individual.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p185}} By 1925 the Faith was in about 50 counties - about 2% - and almost all major urban centers in the Northeast and West Coast excepting Denver, Omaha, Atlanta, Augusta, Miami, and St. Augustine.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p276}} Hampson argued that unity struggles to accept leadership circa 1921-1925 showed some areas lost membership compared to before - only the early cores of communities by 1906 maintained their community populations.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp276-7}} From 1925 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds diffused into nearby regions with infilling and coalescence which favored local spread of the religion while the First Seven Year Plan was the one that established wider diffusion than just in the Northeast and West.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p277}} Those national goals were fulfilled in major urban centers. From 1944 the local diffusion process remained in place since there was no regional goals.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp277-8}} In the earlier period the focus of Shoghi Effendi was to raise administrative structure and initial work raising the Temple<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p196}} out of which, for example, rose a single national budget,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p198}} while afterwards from 1937 almost the exclusive goal was on dispersal of the community.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp198-9}}\n\nHampson generated maps of relative presence of communities and migrations up to 1936.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp260,264}} He noted a number of points.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p265}} While some of the growth in California was from immigration from the rest of the country more was actually by local conversion. The state of New York held its population of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds steady even with the heaviest emigration out of the state of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the country. Illinois and Wisconsin also held steady with both had heavy immigration and emigration. Hampson also observed that most of the migration that occurred was far and westward and little close and southward. Interestingly rates of conversion in a state paralleled rates of migration to a state for most states,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp265-6}} and for a time migration became the principle mechanism of the spread of the Faith where it had not been present before.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p269}} The domestic goal of First Seven Year Plan included reaching an assembly status of every state whether the entire state had 110000 people (Nevada,) or over 6 million, (Texas.)<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p267}} Raising one assembly per state in the South did not rise to proportionality with the state population while to the West it did.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p269}}\n\nTwo individual's cards have been published in biographies: Louis Gregory<ref name=Morrison/>{{rp|pp208-9}} and Alain Locke.<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Buck|title=Alain Locke: Faith and Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JR_DF2MRlsIC&pg=PA58|year=2005|publisher=Kalimat Press|isbn=978-1-890688-38-7|oclc=238582593|page=58}}</ref>\n\n==The black community==\nIn Hampson's analysis, within the group of respondents in view of the total population of the country, the percentage of black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds is lower than in the general percentage of blacks across the whole of America but they were also relatively sparse in those states with most of the Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed population,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp333-5}} but this might also be an effect of urban vs rural concentrations - there were also more cities in the North with Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00eds than more rural regions in the South.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p335}}\n\nIf you profile the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community only in the states they were well established in 1936<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p333}} the per capita representation of blacks in the community was higher than whites - though the absolute population of blacks in the Survey was near 5% of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds that group was more numerous among the black populations of those regions than the white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were of the white population.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} The rate of blacks per million of their population in states with Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in 1936 was 37 whereas for the whites it was 29 per million.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} That's near a third higher rate of adoption among blacks than whites proportional to their population in the states under consideration. Green speculated the religion \"was at one time a very prominent feature of Black America.\u201d<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}}\n\nGreen identified 88 respondents by 1935 were black vs Morrison\u2019s review of 99 by 1937.<ref name=Morrison/> Hampson says 97 respondents to the Survey were black.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} Morrison and Green observed that the black respondents may have been under-surveyed for a number of reasons: the consequences of conscious or unconscious attitudes of the white majority, the unequal effects of the Great Depression, educational disadvantages and being disheartened have to race-conscious questions, and since the Survey was mediated by assemblies regions without assemblies, like the entire South, the black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the South would not likely have heard of the Survey through the institutional call for the Survey. However, both also thought the Survey was a valuable tool to profile the black community and experience as Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in general terms. \n\nLouis Gregory was the earliest black Bah\u00e1'\u00ed of the respondents<ref name=Morrison/> though others are known before him. According to the Survey only five blacks had joined the religion in the South,<ref name=Morrison/> but near 60% were born in the South and near 70% had joined the Faith in the Northern area.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p37}} \n\nGreen discerned two bumps in the overall rate of declarant blacks. One phase of enrollment among African-Americans was discerned between 1913-1920 (for 16 of the 88,)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|pp38-9}} and another between 1927-1933 (36 of 88.)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} He concluded the [[Race Amity Conventions]] were not directly correlated with either group, having mostly run from 1921 to 1933 though they probably were places of an initial introduction to the Faith - cities that had hosted them only had five black enrollments while Seattle gathered four on its own.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p40}} The largest concentration of people of color who responded to the Survey was in DC and it was also the location of the earlier of the two bumps in the rate of black adherents,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p36}} who in general learned of the Faith from white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p38}} The later phase of enhanced adherence was in Chicago and almost all were female who had been born in the South,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} and learned of the Faith in a context of other black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p40}} This development in Chicago started from 1912 with 2 individuals and few by 14 after 1922.<ref name=StockmanThD/> Zia Bagdadi, a Persian Bah\u00e1'\u00ed long living in American, crossed the lines of violence during the [[Chicago race riot of 1919]] where he was noted he was \"the one white man who went into the African-American sections during the riot and brought food to the hungry.\u201d<ref name=Morrison/>{{rp|p130}} According to Gregory Bagdadi was shot at by both white and black protestors on his trips including to see Mr. and Mrs. Clark, black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, who's house had been attacked, themselves arrested and released when cleared by testimony of Bagdadi.<ref>{{cite news\n | author =Louis G. Gregory\n |author-link=Louis G. Gregory\n | title =Baha'i Activities\n | newspaper =Washington Bee\n | location =Washington, DC\n | page =7\n | date = Aug 30, 1919\n | url =https://www.genealogybank.com/doc/newspapers/image/v2%3A12B2E340B2C9FFB8%40GB3NEWS-12BA626919BA1EE0%402422201-12B9B0BE61DA3E98%406-12DD02CA6C269CC0%40 \n | access-date =Feb 17, 2020 }}{{subscription required}}</ref> Mark Perry identifies the wife as Mary (Byron) Clark(e).<ref>* {{cite magazine\n | last =Perry\n | first = Mark\n | title =Pioneering Race Unity: The Chicago Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, 1919-1939\n | magazine =World Order\n | pages =41-60\n | volume =20 |issue=2 |editor1= Firuz Kazemzadeh |editor2= Betty Fisher |editor3= Howard Garey |editor4= James D. Stokes\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the United States\n | date =1986\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:World_Order2_Vol20_Issue2.pdf&page=43\n | access-date =Feb 17, 2020}}\n* {{cite magazine\n | last =Perry\n | first = Mark\n | title =Robert S. Abbottt and the Chicago Defender: A door to the masses\n | magazine =World Order\n | pages =14-24\n | volume =26 |issue=4 |editor1= Firuz Kazemzadeh |editor2= Betty Fisher |editor3= Howard Garey |editor4= James D. Stokes\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the United States\n | date =1995\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:World_Order2_Vol26_Issue4.pdf&page=16 \n | access-date =Feb 17, 2020}}</ref> Among this group of black Chicago Bah\u00e1'\u00eds was [[Robert Sengstacke Abbott]] in 1934, publisher of the ''[[Chicago Defender]]''.\n\nBy 1936 the most common black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were female between 29 and 35 years of age(though also older),<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|pp47,54}} only been a Bah\u00e1'\u00ed few years (mostly since 1933),<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|pp58-9}} highly educated,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} married without children,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p57}} been born in the South (such as Alabama, Georgia, Texas or Florida,)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p55}} identified as black or mixed race,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p60}} and moved to the North, usually to Illinois or New York<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} (secondarily to Maine, Ohio, or DC - or to the West Coast,)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p55}} employed as a teacher or social worker, been a social activist such as in YWCA/YMCA, NAACP or Urban League organizations, as well as members in Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Assemblies.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p48}} Green also commented that when blacks joined many Christian churches it became a crisis that split many of them. From biographical information outside the Survey of known black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds Green also observed that more than a few black adherents were from upper-middle class situations.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} \n\n===The African-American Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by the end of the ministry of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1===\nMorrison's tabulation specifies who had become Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by 1921, the completion of the ministry of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1, and can be compared at least regionally with a recent scholarly enumeration published in 2018.<ref name=BuckPupil>{{cite book|editor=Loni Bramson|title=The Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Faith and African American History: Creating Racial and Religious Diversity|chapter=The Baha\u2019i \u2018Pupil of the Eye\u2019 metaphor |author=Christopher Buck |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stB-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA20 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stB-DwAAQBAJ |date=4 December 2018|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-7003-9 |oclc= 1098186570 |pages=20\u20131}}</ref>\n\nA crude analysis by geography by 1921:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! By 1921 via Morrison\u2019s tabulation<ref name=Morrison/> !! By 1921 via \u201cPupil\u201d enumerated<ref name=BuckPupil/> !! Remainders in Morrison\u2019s not in \u201cPupil\u201d\n|-\n|   || 1 Pleasanton CA ||  \n|-\n| 3 in Chicago || 1 Chicago || 2 unknown from Chicago\n|-\n| 6 in DC || 18 in DC  ||  \n|-\n| 2 in San Francisco ||  2 San Francisco || \n|-\n| 4 adults +4 children in Boston || 3 Boston || ~1-4 unknown from Boston including children\n|-\n| 5 in New York || 5 New York ||  \n|-\n| 1 in Portland, OR || 1 Portland, OR ||  \n|-\n| 2 in Seattle ||   || 2 unknown from Seattle\n|-\n| 1 in Minneapolis ||   || 1 unknown from Minneapolis\n|-\n| 1 in Montclair, NJ ||   || 1 unknown from Montclair, NJ\n|-\n|   || 1 in Charleston, SC ||\n|-\n|   || 1 Richmond, VA ||  \n|-\n|   || 4 Cleveland  ||  \n|-\n|  || 1 Nashville, TN ||  \n|-\n|   || 1 Wilmington, NC ||\n|-\n|   || 1 Harper\u2019s Ferry, WV ||  \n|-\n|  ||   ||  \n|-\n| Total of 29 || Total of 40 || about 11 geographically distinguishable\n|}\nWhile those comparisons suggest about 50, Hampson estimated the complete black Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community of 1936 to be between 110 and 150.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}}\n\nChristopher Buck's 2018 enumeration by 1921 includes some notable people:<ref name=BuckPupil/> [[Robert Turner]], [[Louis Gregory]], [[Harriet Gibbs Marshall]], [[Coralie Franklin Cook]], [[Sadie and Mabry Oglesby|Mabry C. Oglesby, Sadie Oglesby]], and [[Alain Leroy Locke]].\n\nIn later times the black segment of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community grew to about 23% approaching 1980 in Los Angeles.<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p46}}\n\n==The white community==\nHampson reviewed the entirety of the respondents (US and Canada) for details but since the vast majority were white, the general characterizations in most ways are being reviewed in the context of the white community though there were more black respondents<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} than Canadians.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p323}}\n\nOf the white respondents almost 70% were female amidst a community that highly variable and never above 3000 total until the 1940s.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p323}} The proportion of males decreased most of the decades since the religion was established in America. Whites in the community by then were most underrepresented relative to the population at large among those younger than the group 35-40 years old.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp324-6}} The percentage of males peaked around age 45-54 and females had a broad flat high from 40 to 65 - so that the proportion of Bah\u00e1'\u00ed women per age group increased until very late in age - 70 and above. That peak was at a rate around 45 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds per million. The rate of Baha\u2019i membership compared to the national population about matches the mean population age at about near age 45 combining men and women.\n\nHampson observed the overall structure of the age profile of the respondents was natural from increasing age once declared.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p327}} He compared the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed population by age with a simple model from which he made some conclusions:<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp331-2}} there is a broadly near linear increase percentage of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in a rising age range among those still in the religion by 1936 affected only by the overall mortality rate and the overall increase in the size of the whole country, and there was a sharp increase in the adoption of the religion since 1926 and even higher from 1932.\n\nOrientalist scholar E. G. Browne wrote a testimonial obituary for \u2018Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 in January 1922 published in the ''The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland'' wherein he says:<blockquote>One of the most notable practical results of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed ethical teaching in the United States has been, according to the recent testimony of an impartial and qualified observer, the establishment in Bah\u00e1'\u00ed circles in New York of a real fraternity between black and white, and an unprecedented lifting of the \u2018colour bar\u2019, described by the said observer as \u2019almost miraculous\u2019. <ref>{{cite journal\n | author= E. G. Browne\n | author-link = E. G. Browne\n | title = Sir 'Abdu'l-Baha 'Abbas: Died 28th November, 1921\n | journal =The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland\n | volume =1922\n | issue =1\n | pages =145-146\n | publisher =Cambridge University Press\n | date =Jan 1922\n | url =https://www.jstor.org/stable/25209873?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents\n | jstor =25209873\n | issn =0035-869X\n | oclc= 5543871171\n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref></blockquote> An antagonistic attention against this engagement of the religion is to be found. A KKK newspaper<ref>{{cite book|editor1=David J. Bodenhamer|editor2=Robert G. Barrows|title=The Encyclopedia of Indianapolis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bg13QcMSsq8C|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bg13QcMSsq8C&pg=PA566|chapter=The Fiery Cross |author=Patricia Fogleman|date=22 November 1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-11249-4|page=566}}</ref> ''[[The_Fiery_Cross_(newsletter)|The Fiery Cross]]'' had an entry against the \"Bahaists and Babist\" in New York.<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Heathenism within our borders\n | newspaper =The Fiery Cross\n | location =Indianapolis, IN |editor= Ernest W Reichard| volume=2|number=9\n | page =4\n | date =Feb 2, 1923\n | url =http://bl-libg-doghill.ads.iu.edu/gpd-web/fierycross/192322/192322.pdf \n | access-date = Feb 15, 2020}}</ref> On the other hand a 1925 brief profile of the religion in the African-American newspaper the ''New York Age'' sums it up: \u201cThat is quite a volume of advanced beliefs to introduce in one movement.\"<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Among the imported cults which has found lodgment in this country\u2026\n | newspaper =The New York Age\n | location =New York NY\n | page =7\n | date =26 September 1925\n | url =http://www.newspapers.com/clip/269138/profile_of_bahai_faith_from_holding_a/ \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> In 1927 note was taken of the election of [[Louis Gregory]] echoing coverage in ''The Washington Sentinel'' on the election of Gregory exemplifying the \"spirit of racial amity\" at the 19th convention electing the National Spiritual Assembly.<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Comments by the Age Editors on sayings of other editors\n | newspaper =The New York Age\n | location =New York, NY\n | page =4\n | date =23 July 1927\n | url =http://www.newspapers.com/clip/269247/the_new_york_age/ \n | access-date = Feb 15, 2020}}</ref> Despite all this no significant growth in the black community arose in New York by 1936 according to the Survey.<ref name=StockmanThD/>\n\nHampson found that the whites were mostly Anglo-Saxon/British and almost completely that group plus the northern European (German/Scandinavian) with only a very small percent eastern or southern European though this approximates the general population well.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp335-7}} Among the whites the suggestion from Hampson is that the background affecting attraction to the religion was not their ethnic heritage but one of previous religious experience.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p338}}\n\n=== Religious motivations and characterization===\nMost white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the time were elderly white women of British background who had been Unitarian/Universalist or at least one of the liberal denominations (Episcopal and Congregational) of Christianity.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp344-5}} The Unitarian/Universalist position is nominally closer to the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed position on the Christian idea of the trinity as well as the importance of a reasoned faith compared to dogma or church authority.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp342-3}} \n\nSmith proposed the members of the religious sub-groups were underreported into the mainstream groups for the Survey and by relying on anecdotal mention of various individual Bah\u00e1'\u00eds discerned some subgroups may have been important - millenaries<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p155}} (especially Adventism<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p156}}), metaphysical esotericism and quest (especially the search going through Christian Science, New Thought and Theosophy,)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp162-3}}), religious liberalism(its inclusiveness,)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p171}} having a sense of a need for social reconstruction,<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p179}} and personal attachment to 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 (usually as the presence of the Christ spirit or more<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp182-3}} which transformed into an appreciation of the Covenant<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p179}}.) \n\nSmith supported the millenaries group by anecdotally referring to several individuals, publications, and Greenacre reports and the advent issues featured in discussions of 1914 and 1917 though not generally circulated.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp156-7}} Many presentations limited the unveiling of the ideas of [[End time]] era with the quick arrival at its conclusion without \"apocalyptic horrors\u201d but was referenced in 1914, linked with the Christian Era year 70 and destruction of Jerusalem and the Temple with the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Era 70( which was in 1914.)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p158}} This was added to with optimism that peace would be the natural consequence of the war period and according to one report was the key discussion of the national convention.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p159}} Smith described the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed sense of millenarianism as more on the side of post-millenarianism theology, looking for a present active reconstruction of society, and that Bah\u00e1'\u00eds definitely had some [[Adventism]] mixed in as well.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p160}}\n\nFor the metaphysical movement being an appreciable part of the religious background of the white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, especially New Thought and Theosophy - following a religious search often away from the mainstreams<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p161}} - Smith observed that during 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1\u2019s tour in America in general and at Greenacre featured meetings with such groups, and the presence of Bah\u00e1'\u00ed membership in the Chicago New Thought Executive Committee.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp162-3}} But this group also had a strain with the anti-individualistic approach to the religious priority of its leadership before 1919,<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p164}} and led to an ambivalent co-existent relationship until there were greater tensions later.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p165}} There were new patterns of authority sanctioned while old methods of authority were rejected. Tolerance for non-scriptural practices was allowed but not endorsed albeit some were opposed like the belief in reincarnation. Some of these beliefs that were specifically opposed continued anyway but opposition to claims of personal authority was a greater issue - there were claims of individual conscience and special powers.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p167}} However no process of these claims led to recognized authority in the religion though sometimes lasting or widespread recognition did exist and did lead to cliques and confusions.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p168}} Secret meeting circles occurred which may have been largest in the case of W. H. Harmon who personally revered 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 and associated with the community and teachings but did not join the community. This led to the Committee of Inquiry of 1917-1918,<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p170}} (aka Reading Room Affair.)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p189}} The group calling itself the Reading Room, avowing Harmon's personal authority, sent delegates to national convention and was challenged by Chicago House of Spirituality in Boston in 1917 - the findings of a committee were supported by attendees of 19 communities followed by essays about the affair in 1918.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp189-90}} Criticisms included they were leading people astray who used occult pretensions to seek money. The 1918 convention was meticulously reviewed for delegate credentials and the convention approved the committee's findings.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp190-1}}\n\nSmith characterized the religious liberalism component of the white population's religious background as having arose out of protestant transformation toward social Christianity between the Civil War and WWI and it was itself opposed by a rise of fundamentalism.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p170}} The liberalism motivations made repeated statements of inclusiveness of ideas, to add to one\u2019s belief from other places, other religions, an approach of being \u201cleaven rather than a cult\u201d and a challenge \"to be more true to what is deepest in their faith\u201d<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp171-2}} while upholding the singular authority of Bah\u00e1\u2019u\u2019ll\u00e1h followed by 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 and not break ties with previous religious affiliations and even used their presence in them to present Bah\u00e1'\u00ed ideas to them.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p173}} The ambiguous liberalism had strains in relation to the Faith being a distinct set of principles.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p174}} The liberalism emphasized a \u201clive the life\u201d pattern of action and sometimes as collective action. Smith notes peace organizations and race issues seeming to be the broadest efforts associated with this mindset of previous thinking and many audiences occurred of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 and Bah\u00e1'\u00eds with organizations of like mind:<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p175}} NAACP, Bowery Mission, Jane Addams Hull House but also volunteers to the League of Nations to enforce peace though how to proceed was not agreed.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p177}} \n\n'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1\u2019s personal standing among many was combined with his personal style of tolerance and gradualism though this leveraged peaceable if opposition to existing worldly authority.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p181}} In Britain the appreciation of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 was less of a high station <ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p182}} and the Americans offended the Londoners with their acts of personal devotion.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp181-2}} Nevertheless the primacy of `Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 of whatever appreciation was a unifying factor in the American Bah\u00e1'\u00ed experience and rose in time in the form of an understanding of the [[Lesser Covenant]] against the challenges of other points of view.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p183}}\n\n==After 1936==\nDuring the first Seven Year Plan, 1936-1944, 153 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds moved among the goal areas in America that succeeded in electing assemblies - an average of 6 per goal area.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp269-70}} A few local residents must have joined in - and in some areas more and in some areas less.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p270}} An additional 10 moved to areas that did not elect an assembly by 1944, another 42 moved to areas in Canada and Alaska and 24 moved to areas that became jeopardized. Altogether 248 moved - 10% of the community for the domestic goals alone. There was also an international goal was one assembly per country of the Western Hemisphere.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p270}} In addition to intranational pioneers, at least some 28 pioneers and more than 30 traveling Bah\u00e1'\u00eds registered their trips for the religion set off to 19 Latin American countries.<ref>* {{cite book\n| author=Louie A. Mathews\n | title =The Baha'i Centenary 1844-1944\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of the United States |chapter= Baha'i teaching in Latin America to 1940\n | date =1944\n | location =Wilmette, IL\n | pages =195-200\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File%3ACentenary-1844-1944.pdf |chapter-url=https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Centenary-1844-1944.pdf&page=216 \n | oclc= 270631500}}\n* {{cite book\n | author=Artemus Lamb\n | title =The Beginnings of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in Latin America: Some Remembrances |chapter=First pioneers, believers, and assemblies in each country\n | publisher =VanOrman Enterprises\n | edition =English Revised and Amplified\n | date =  November 1995\n | location =San Salvador\n | language =Spanish\n | url =https://bahai-library.com/lamb_bahai_latin_america |chapter-url=https://bahai-library.com/lamb_bahai_latin_america#7}}</ref> Hampson observed a significant effect internationally was the role of individuals as well.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p358}} \n\nA few individuals have been found noteworthy in raising up communities in the country.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Women in the North American Baha'i Community |author1=Sandra Hutchinson |author2= Richard Hollinger| editor= Rosemary Skinner Keller |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of women and religion in North America |volume= 2 |year= 2006 |publisher=Indiana Univ. Press |location=Bloomington, IN |isbn= 9780253346858 | oclc= 836273399 |page= 779 }}</ref> Three ladies were noted who \"single-handedly\" established new communities by giving public lectures on then-popular topics and then inviting people to attend a series of classes on the religion. The number of local assemblies in America doubled from 1937 to 1945.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p364}} Another factor was in the size which continued to be a key dynamic of the community - a tendency to encourage Bah\u00e1'\u00eds to spread out to form more communities rather than larger communities once it reached about 15 adult active members of the community which has been documented from the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Goals for this Baha'i Year\n | newspaper =Baha'i News\n | page =5\n | date =May 1948 |number=207\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Baha%27i_News_207.pdf&page=5 \n | access-date = }}</ref> The average size of the community with assemblies in 1936 was 30 adults which dropped to 15 in 1947 and 14.2 in 1991; 15 was seen as ideal community size after 1936 and there was encouragement to spread out at that point and to go to small towns after 1976.<ref name=Holinger>{{cite book\n | author= Richard Hollinger\n | title =Community Histories |chapter=Introduction\n | publisher = Kailmat Press\n | series =Studies in the Babi and Baha\u2019i Religions\n | volume =6 |editor1= Richard Hollinger |editor2= series editor Anthony A. Lee\n | date =1992\n | location =Los Angeles, CA\n | pages = xxix, xxx, xxxiv, xxxix\n | oclc=32305770\n | isbn = 9780933770768 }}</ref> In the winter of 1952-3 the Guardian said to disperse even for the largest communities,<ref>{{cite news\n | title =On the character and purpose of the world crusade; Jubilee Celebration |author=Ruhiyyih Khanum\n | newspaper =Baha'i News\n | page =22\n | date =May 6, 1953\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Jubilee_Celebration_1953.pdf&page=22 \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> and on 28 May 1953 called for dispersal of pioneers to virgin areas and continued in later years.<ref>* {{cite book\n | author=Lewis Ware\n | title =Baha'i World |chapter=In memoriam; Elizabeth S. Laws, 1888-1977, Knight of Baha'u'llah\n | publisher =Universal House of Justice\n | series =An International Record\n | volume =17\n | date =1981\n | location =Haifa, Israel\n | page =459\n | url = https://bahai.works/Bah\u00e1\u2019%C3%AD_World/Volume_17 |chapter-url=https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:BW_Volume17.pdf&page=479 \n | isbn = 9780853981305\n |oclc= 461956705 }}\n* {{cite news\n | title =National Spiritual Assembly; The home front teaching plan; The Role of Assemblies\n | newspaper = Baha'i News\n | page =6\n | date = Jun 1954\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Baha%27i_News_280.pdf&page=6 \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}\n* {{cite news\n | title =All-Alaska teaching conference\n | newspaper =Baha'i News\n | page =7\n | date =Oct 1955 |number=296\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Baha%27i_News_296.pdf&page=7 \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}\n* {{cite news\n | title = The Guardian called for dispersal on the home front\n | newspaper = US Supplement to the Baha'i News\n | page =2\n | date =October 1962\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:US_Supplement_56.pdf&page=2\n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> In the 1960s the act of local incorporation was suggested for a community with a minimum of 15 adults,<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Letter from the National Spiritual Assembly\n | newspaper =US Supplement to the Baha'i News\n | page =1\n | date =Aug 1965\n | url =https://bahai.works/File:US_Supplement_90.pdf\n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> and individuals living in communities with more than 15 were asked to spread out to sustain spiritual assemblies.<ref>{{cite book |author=Mike McMullen |title=The Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00eds of America: The Growth of a Religious Movement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iecWCgAAQBAJ |date=27 November 2015 |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-1-4798-5152-2 |oclc= 1136454836 |page=133}}</ref>\n\n==Opposition and opportunity==\nHampson observed most of the spread of the Faith over the long term has followed the three variables: higher area basic population, socio-economic dynamism, and highway penetration.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p305}} He noticed an oppositional area however - that by 1980 \u201cBaha\u2019is fail to be present where one might expect \u2026throughout a very large wedge that extends eastward (from the Great Plains) and gradually curls around the southern portions of Illinois, Indiana, and Ohio, terminating [into] the southern flank of Pennsylvania [and a] tiny prong \u2026 reaches the Atlantic via southern Virginia.\u201d<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p298}} Hampson doesn\u2019t name this region but much of it is pretty much the middle and northern [[Confederate_States_of_America#Span_of_control|span of control of the Confederacy]] when it isn\u2019t an urban center. Some of this region fits the lack of dynamism and highway accessibility but not enough to explain the overall relative gap in Hampson's estimation.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp297-8}}\n\nThis is contrasted with the unusual acceptance of the religion, in Hampson's analysis, along the northern regions of the Union especially along the Canadian border and then along the Gulf and southeast coast, to favoring the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, which Hampson speculates might be due to the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds reaching out to the black community,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p300}} which he notes more clearly since 1954.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p315}} The region of resistance is also cut by some growth along the highways and towards larger urbanized areas from Chicago and the states near and west of Chicago (Illinois, Wisconsin, Minnesota, Iowa and Missouri),<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp312-3}} and in mid-Atlantic part of the South - Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina into South Carolina and Georgia which was largely more urbanized in larger population centers.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp314-5}}\n\nBah\u00e1'\u00eds were more concentrated in larger cities before 1936 and this was cut to less than half by 1976.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp312-3}} Circa 1976 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds favored towns up to 45000 people even above that of the national population and lived in major cities at the lowest rate.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp308-9}} At the rate per million of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the modern era, on average a town or county area of about 45000 people has enough people to form an assembly whereas larger cities with larger numbers of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds could have larger numbers leave and not affect assembly status.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p311}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "The 1934-1936 '''Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Historical Record Survey''' (also called \"cards\") was an early demographic review of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the  United States]] and Canada. The backgrounds of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were later studied in a number of ways - racial and ethnic heritage, previous religious background, geographical spread and sometimes how these have changed over the years. Complimentary data sources have also been used to add to some of the reviews including US Census publications and Bah\u00e1'\u00ed directories published in periodicals of [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed literature]]. \n\nA couple of these studies look specifically at the burgeoning black population of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds amidst the wider society practice of continuing [[Racial_segregation_in_the_United_States#New_Deal_era|era of social segregation in the American society of the time]] which was against the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed teaching of the [[Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed Faith and the unity of humanity|unity of all humanity]]. The vast majority of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were white and mostly elder women, but the black segment of those states Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were in responded more to the religion than the white population of those states did. The religion was also initially attracting Protestants, especially Unitarian Universalists and also among other more mainstream liberal denominations, but as history approached 1936 and beyond it attracted a greater diversity of religious backgrounds as it continued to grow more by conversion than by migration. However intentional migration had been undertaken shortly after this time - the religion had only been present in a few states mostly in the Northeast to North Central and West Coast coming up to 1936 but a goal was set to spread the religion to every state by 1944. As it spread inward from the West coast this mere presence established recognizable proportional membership in the population while in the higher population of the South it did not. But there it did take root too, more so among the black communities along the coastal regions of the South. Indeed this wave of activity was undertaken during the first Seven Year Plan established by [[Shoghi Effendi]] which had the intranational goal as well as a goal for establishing the religion in the countries of Latin America.\n\n==Development, context, and reviews of the Survey==\nThe 1934 American national convention affirmed the request of the national race amity committee for a survey of the racial makeup of the community affirming the request of the national amity committee work asking for localized amity committees and consolidation with concerned groups like the NAACP and Urban League.<ref name=GreenThesis>{{cite thesis |author=Jerome Green|date=2004 |title=Trial and Triumph: The Origins of the Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Faith in Black America |type=Senior Fellowship Thesis|publisher=Dartmouth College |oclc= 242842724 |url=http://bahai-library.com/green_bahai_black_america |access-date=Feb 9, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|p36}} The same year the national youth committee including [[Marion Holley]] recommended a census be taken of youth as well.<ref>{{cite magazine | title =Youth committee | magazine = Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00ed News | pages = 23\u20134 | date = May 1934|issue= 74 | url = http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=01&page=601 | access-date =Dec 29, 2017}}</ref> The Survey developed included historical information of the respondent - the date and place they were born, the date and place they joined the religion, and where they were living at the time of the Survey as well as their national and religious background.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p66}}\n\nThe Survey was widespread by the summer of 1935.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p37}} The complete collection of respondents is a little unclear. There have been four reviews of the Survey: \n* In 1980 Arthur Hampson did a geography PhD using the Survey as one of his main sources of information to review the development of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community using more demographic information.<ref name=HampsonPhD>{{cite thesis |last=Hampson |first=Arthur |date=May 1980 |title= The growth and spread of the Baha'i Faith |type=PhD |publisher=Department of Geography, University of Hawaii |id= UMI 8022655|oclc=652914306 |url= https://bahai-library.com/hampson_growth_spread_bahai|access-date=Feb 10, 2020}}</ref> \n* In 1982 Gayle Morrison included an analysis of the black community from the 1936 Survey in her biography of Hand of the Cause [[Louis G. Gregory]].<ref name=Morrison>{{cite book|author=Gayle Morrison|title=To Move the World: Louis G. Gregory and the Advancement of Racial Unity in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tl8wAAAAYAAJ |date=1 January 1982|publisher=Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Pub. Trust|isbn=978-0-87743-171-8|oclc= 988271963|pages=203-9}}</ref>\n* In 1982 Peter Smith used the Survey via a selection of every third respondent<ref name=SmithStudiesv1>{{cite book\n | author= Peter Smith\n | author-link = Peter Smith\n | title =Studies in Babi and Baha\u02bci History |chapter=The American Baha\u02bci community, 1894-1917: A preliminary survey\n | publisher =Kalimat Press\n | volume =1 |editor= [[Moojan Momen]]\n | date =1982\n | location =Los Angeles\n | oclc= 863423149\n | isbn =9780933770164}}</ref>{{rp|p118}} to review the religion and examined the depth of religious backgrounds that could be perceived in anecdotes of the backgrounds of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by then. Smith did a second review of the data published in 2004 mostly looking at comparisons with other surveys in other times and places.<ref name=BFitW-Smith>{{cite book|author=Peter Smith|editor=Peter Smith |series=Studies in the B\u00e1b\u00ed and Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Religions|volume=14|editor2=Anthony L. Lee |title=Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the West|chapter=The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the West: A Survey|pages=3-60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x7wyJdyE60oC|year=2004|publisher=Kalimat Press|isbn=978-1-890688-11-0}}</ref>\n* Robert Stockman included a review of the Survey especially for members of three communities in his PhD in 1990 including transcribing all of the physical cards into a computer file.<ref name=StockmanThD>{{cite thesis |last=Stockman |first=Robert H. |date=January 1990 |title=The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith and American Protestantism |type= ThD |publisher= Harvard Divinity School |oclc= 23934626 |pages=43-58 |url= |access-date=}}</ref>\n* In 2004 Gerome Green finished a senior thesis at Dartmouth College also reviewing the Survey for a look at the black community.<ref name=GreenThesis/> \nHampson counted 1784 respondents<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p323}} of which 1729 were from the United States proper.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p320}} Morrison and Stockman counted 1813 by 1936-7.<ref name=Morrison/><ref name=StockmanThD/> Smith's sample approach would have totaled about 1803.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p118}} Stockman collected the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed population up to about 1936 finding about 4000 people had joined the religion up to then.<ref name=stockmanv25n3>{{cite journal\n | last =Stockman\n | first =Robert \n | author-link =Robert Stockman\n | title = The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in America: one hundred years\n | journal =World Order\n | volume =25\n | issue =3 |editor1= Firuz Kazemzadeh |editor2= Betty J. Fisher |editor3= Howard Garey |editor4= Robert H. Stockman |editor5= James D. Stokes\n | pages =9-23\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the United States\n | date =1994\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:World_Order2_Vol25_Issue3.pdf&page=11\n | issn = 0043-8804\n | access-date = Feb 14, 2020}}</ref> Unasked for, but some respondents included multi-page autobiographies.<ref name=StockmanThD/>\n\nHampson was able to compare the community Survey with the Census of Religions of the United States for 1936 and early dates<ref name=1936FedCensus>For similar information see US Federal Census referenced the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community in summery for 1936 and briefly of earlier dates: {{cite book|title=Census of Religious Bodies, 1936: Bulletin No. 1 of 78 |volume=2|number=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4gBJZuh2RhAC |chapter=Baha\u2019is| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4gBJZuh2RhAC&pg=PA76 |year=1941|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|pages=76\u201382}}</ref> which counted 2584 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the continental US in 1936. The census information was gathered from the respective religious communities - no additional censuses were done.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p137}} So the national assembly's survey represented about 70% of the community of the US and Canada as understood by the national assembly. Still the Survey had the lowest percentage of responses in New York(mostly the city) and Illinois(mostly Chicago) and highest in the whole West.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p321}}\n\n==The overall community ==\nStockman estimated, partly on the basis of the Survey, that roughly 50-100 people identified as Bah\u00e1'\u00eds during the time 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 was in America in 1912.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert H. Stockman|author-link=Robert H. Stockman|title=\u02bbAbdu\u02bcl-Bah\u00e1 in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0enOpwAACAAJ|year=2012|publisher=Baha'i Pub.|isbn=978-1-931847-97-1|pages=362-3}}</ref>\n\nSmith broke down the respondents who were Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by 1919, a total of 197 individuals still alive and members of the community by 1936: 90% were northern European (British, German, Scandinavian, generally \u201cwhite\u201d without ethnic background specified,) 6% African-American, but absent any Southern or Eastern European and Irish.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp118-9}}<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p47}} This population was previously 33% of mainstream Protestant Christian background (Episcopal, Methodist, Congregationalist, Presbyterian and Baptist,) 11% Lutheran, 5% Unitarian/Universalist, followed distantly at 3% by metaphysical denominations (Swedenborgian, Christian Science, Theosophy and New Thought,) while a definite if small overall presence was of those raised in Bah\u00e1'\u00ed homes.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp119-20}} Or, put another way by Smith in 2004: 56% Protestant of any stripe, 17% \"Christian\", 5% Catholic, 2-3% Jewish, and 4-5% Bah\u00e1'\u00ed.<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p49}} The overall pattern of a few percent raised Bah\u00e1'\u00ed was shown to be the case in a number of other surveys, (outside the Persian community in the West that arrived later.)<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p49}} It was also 66% women.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p121}}\n\nStockman broke down the communities of New York city, Chicago, and Kenosha, and across time, for what details they provided. Those three communities were significantly different:<ref name=StockmanThD/> Kenosha was mostly Scandinavians and Germans, with mostly early converts being 1st generation immigrants, Chicago started with half American followed by English and German and added a significant black proportion of the community after 1921, and in New York the community identified as mostly American then English, and then added a proportion of German. His analysis also showed broadly similar patterns in the communities of Christian or Protestant groups which started out a dominant group and dropped percentage-wise approaching 1936 while those raised as Bah\u00e1'\u00eds kept increasing with a couple small groups non-Protestants, (Catholics, Jews, or metaphysical groups) adding in as well: it started out more Protestant than the US in general but became more diverse than the US in general.<ref name=StockmanThD/>\n\nHampson analyzed the Survey and Census results relative to the states that had a Bah\u00e1'\u00ed population, a minority of the states mostly in the upper mid-West to the Northeast and California, and compared the racial and religious groups for just those states. He argued that the rate of black declarants in those states was much higher than being proportional to the black population of those states, indeed their rate of affiliation with the religion was above that of the rate of white presence in those states,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp333-5}} and, though fewer of the Survey respondents were sufficiently particular about their religious background, agreed they were mostly from a Protestant background with the refinement that the contribution of the Unitarians was well above that of their proportion of their presence in those states and above that of all other protestant denominations though Episcopalian and Congregational were nearly tied for a distant second.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp338-342}} The lowest rate of religious backgrounds relative to their population in the states with significant Bah\u00e1'\u00eds presence were those of Jewish and Catholic backgrounds.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p340}} However Stockman characterizes these groups as contributing significantly to the religious diversity of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community,<ref name=stockmanv25n3/> and Smith also that in other surveys at other times Jews showed a significantly higher percentage of some communities.<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|pp49-50}}\n\nHampson was able to do a county-by-county analysis including of earlier times.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p274}} By 1919 most Bah\u00e1'\u00ed communities had less than two dozen adults and many were an isolated group or individual.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p185}} By 1925 the Faith was in about 50 counties - about 2% - and almost all major urban centers in the Northeast and West Coast excepting Denver, Omaha, Atlanta, Augusta, Miami, and St. Augustine.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p276}} Hampson argued that unity struggles to accept leadership circa 1921-1925 showed some areas lost membership compared to before - only the early cores of communities by 1906 maintained their community populations.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp276-7}} From 1925 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds diffused into nearby regions with infilling and coalescence which favored local spread of the religion while the First Seven Year Plan was the one that established wider diffusion than just in the Northeast and West.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p277}} Those national goals were fulfilled in major urban centers. From 1944 the local diffusion process remained in place since there was no regional goals.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp277-8}} In the earlier period the focus of Shoghi Effendi was to raise administrative structure and initial work raising the Temple<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p196}} out of which, for example, rose a single national budget,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p198}} while afterwards from 1937 almost the exclusive goal was on dispersal of the community.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp198-9}}\n\nHampson generated maps of relative presence of communities and migrations up to 1936.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp260,264}} He noted a number of points.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p265}} While some of the growth in California was from immigration from the rest of the country more was actually by local conversion. The state of New York held its population of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds steady even with the heaviest emigration out of the state of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the country. Illinois and Wisconsin also held steady with both had heavy immigration and emigration. Hampson also observed that most of the migration that occurred was far and westward and little close and southward. Interestingly rates of conversion in a state paralleled rates of migration to a state for most states,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp265-6}} and for a time migration became the principle mechanism of the spread of the Faith where it had not been present before.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p269}} The domestic goal of First Seven Year Plan included reaching an assembly status of every state whether the entire state had 110000 people (Nevada,) or over 6 million, (Texas.)<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p267}} Raising one assembly per state in the South did not rise to proportionality with the state population while to the West it did.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p269}}\n\nTwo individual's cards have been published in biographies: Louis Gregory<ref name=Morrison/>{{rp|pp208-9}} and Alain Locke.<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Buck|title=Alain Locke: Faith and Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JR_DF2MRlsIC&pg=PA58|year=2005|publisher=Kalimat Press|isbn=978-1-890688-38-7|oclc=238582593|page=58}}</ref>\n\n==The black community==\nIn Hampson's analysis, within the group of respondents in view of the total population of the country, the percentage of black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds is lower than in the general percentage of blacks across the whole of America but they were also relatively sparse in those states with most of the Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed population,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp333-5}} but this might also be an effect of urban vs rural concentrations - there were also more cities in the North with Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00eds than more rural regions in the South.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p335}}\n\nIf you profile the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community only in the states they were well established in 1936<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p333}} the per capita representation of blacks in the community was higher than whites - though the absolute population of blacks in the Survey was near 5% of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds that group was more numerous among the black populations of those regions than the white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were of the white population.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} The rate of blacks per million of their population in states with Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in 1936 was 37 whereas for the whites it was 29 per million.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} That's near a third higher rate of adoption among blacks than whites proportional to their population in the states under consideration. Green speculated the religion \"was at one time a very prominent feature of Black America.\u201d<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}}\n\nGreen identified 88 respondents by 1935 were black vs Morrison\u2019s review of 99 by 1937.<ref name=Morrison/> Hampson says 97 respondents to the Survey were black.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} Morrison and Green observed that the black respondents may have been under-surveyed for a number of reasons: the consequences of conscious or unconscious attitudes of the white majority, the unequal effects of the Great Depression, educational disadvantages and being disheartened have to race-conscious questions, and since the Survey was mediated by assemblies regions without assemblies, like the entire South, the black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the South would not likely have heard of the Survey through the institutional call for the Survey. However, both also thought the Survey was a valuable tool to profile the black community and experience as Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in general terms. \n\nLouis Gregory was the earliest black Bah\u00e1'\u00ed of the respondents<ref name=Morrison/> though others are known before him. According to the Survey only five blacks had joined the religion in the South,<ref name=Morrison/> but near 60% were born in the South and near 70% had joined the Faith in the Northern area.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p37}} \n\nGreen discerned two bumps in the overall rate of declarant blacks. One phase of enrollment among African-Americans was discerned between 1913-1920 (for 16 of the 88,)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|pp38-9}} and another between 1927-1933 (36 of 88.)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} He concluded the [[Race Amity Conventions]] were not directly correlated with either group, having mostly run from 1921 to 1933 though they probably were places of an initial introduction to the Faith - cities that had hosted them only had five black enrollments while Seattle gathered four on its own.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p40}} The largest concentration of people of color who responded to the Survey was in DC and it was also the location of the earlier of the two bumps in the rate of black adherents,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p36}} who in general learned of the Faith from white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p38}} The later phase of enhanced adherence was in Chicago and almost all were female who had been born in the South,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} and learned of the Faith in a context of other black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p40}} This development in Chicago started from 1912 with 2 individuals and few by 14 after 1922.<ref name=StockmanThD/> Zia Bagdadi, a Persian Bah\u00e1'\u00ed long living in American, crossed the lines of violence during the [[Chicago race riot of 1919]] where he was noted he was \"the one white man who went into the African-American sections during the riot and brought food to the hungry.\u201d<ref name=Morrison/>{{rp|p130}} According to Gregory Bagdadi was shot at by both white and black protestors on his trips including to see Mr. and Mrs. Clark, black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, who's house had been attacked, themselves arrested and released when cleared by testimony of Bagdadi.<ref>{{cite news\n | author =Louis G. Gregory\n |author-link=Louis G. Gregory\n | title =Baha'i Activities\n | newspaper =Washington Bee\n | location =Washington, DC\n | page =7\n | date = Aug 30, 1919\n | url =https://www.genealogybank.com/doc/newspapers/image/v2%3A12B2E340B2C9FFB8%40GB3NEWS-12BA626919BA1EE0%402422201-12B9B0BE61DA3E98%406-12DD02CA6C269CC0%40 \n | access-date =Feb 17, 2020 }}{{subscription required}}</ref> Mark Perry identifies the wife as Mary (Byron) Clark(e).<ref>* {{cite magazine\n | last =Perry\n | first = Mark\n | title =Pioneering Race Unity: The Chicago Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, 1919-1939\n | magazine =World Order\n | pages =41-60\n | volume =20 |issue=2 |editor1= Firuz Kazemzadeh |editor2= Betty Fisher |editor3= Howard Garey |editor4= James D. Stokes\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the United States\n | date =1986\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:World_Order2_Vol20_Issue2.pdf&page=43\n | access-date =Feb 17, 2020}}\n* {{cite magazine\n | last =Perry\n | first = Mark\n | title =Robert S. Abbottt and the Chicago Defender: A door to the masses\n | magazine =World Order\n | pages =14-24\n | volume =26 |issue=4 |editor1= Firuz Kazemzadeh |editor2= Betty Fisher |editor3= Howard Garey |editor4= James D. Stokes\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the United States\n | date =1995\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:World_Order2_Vol26_Issue4.pdf&page=16 \n | access-date =Feb 17, 2020}}</ref> Among this group of black Chicago Bah\u00e1'\u00eds was [[Robert Sengstacke Abbott]] in 1934, publisher of the ''[[Chicago Defender]]''.\n\nBy 1936 the most common black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds were female between 29 and 35 years of age(though also older),<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|pp47,54}} only been a Bah\u00e1'\u00ed few years (mostly since 1933),<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|pp58-9}} highly educated,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} married without children,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p57}} been born in the South (such as Alabama, Georgia, Texas or Florida,)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p55}} identified as black or mixed race,<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p60}} and moved to the North, usually to Illinois or New York<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} (secondarily to Maine, Ohio, or DC - or to the West Coast,)<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p55}} employed as a teacher or social worker, been a social activist such as in YWCA/YMCA, NAACP or Urban League organizations, as well as members in Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Assemblies.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p48}} Green also commented that when blacks joined many Christian churches it became a crisis that split many of them. From biographical information outside the Survey of known black Bah\u00e1'\u00eds Green also observed that more than a few black adherents were from upper-middle class situations.<ref name=GreenThesis/>{{rp|p41}} \n\n===The African-American Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by the end of the ministry of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1===\nMorrison's tabulation specifies who had become Bah\u00e1'\u00eds by 1921, the completion of the ministry of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1, and can be compared at least regionally with a recent scholarly enumeration published in 2018.<ref name=BuckPupil>{{cite book|editor=Loni Bramson|title=The Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Faith and African American History: Creating Racial and Religious Diversity|chapter=The Baha\u2019i \u2018Pupil of the Eye\u2019 metaphor |author=Christopher Buck |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stB-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA20 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stB-DwAAQBAJ |date=4 December 2018|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-1-4985-7003-9 |oclc= 1098186570 |pages=20\u20131}}</ref>\n\nA crude analysis by geography by 1921:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! By 1921 via Morrison\u2019s tabulation<ref name=Morrison/> !! By 1921 via \u201cPupil\u201d enumerated<ref name=BuckPupil/> !! Remainders in Morrison\u2019s not in \u201cPupil\u201d\n|-\n|   || 1 Pleasanton CA ||  \n|-\n| 3 in Chicago || 1 Chicago || 2 unknown from Chicago\n|-\n| 6 in DC || 18 in DC  ||  \n|-\n| 2 in San Francisco ||  2 San Francisco || \n|-\n| 4 adults +4 children in Boston || 3 Boston || ~1-4 unknown from Boston including children\n|-\n| 5 in New York || 5 New York ||  \n|-\n| 1 in Portland, OR || 1 Portland, OR ||  \n|-\n| 2 in Seattle ||   || 2 unknown from Seattle\n|-\n| 1 in Minneapolis ||   || 1 unknown from Minneapolis\n|-\n| 1 in Montclair, NJ ||   || 1 unknown from Montclair, NJ\n|-\n|   || 1 in Charleston, SC ||\n|-\n|   || 1 Richmond, VA ||  \n|-\n|   || 4 Cleveland  ||  \n|-\n|  || 1 Nashville, TN ||  \n|-\n|   || 1 Wilmington, NC ||\n|-\n|   || 1 Harper\u2019s Ferry, WV ||  \n|-\n|  ||   ||  \n|-\n| Total of 29 || Total of 40 || about 11 geographically distinguishable\n|}\nWhile those comparisons suggest about 50, Hampson estimated the complete black Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community of 1936 to be between 110 and 150.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}}\n\nChristopher Buck's 2018 enumeration by 1921 includes some notable people:<ref name=BuckPupil/> [[Robert Turner]], [[Louis Gregory]], [[Harriet Gibbs Marshall]], [[Coralie Franklin Cook]], [[Sadie and Mabry Oglesby|Mabry C. Oglesby, Sadie Oglesby]], and [[Alain Leroy Locke]].\n\nIn later times the black segment of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed community grew to about 23% approaching 1980 in Los Angeles.<ref name=BFitW-Smith/>{{rp|p46}}\n\n==The white community==\nHampson reviewed the entirety of the respondents (US and Canada) for details but since the vast majority were white, the general characterizations in most ways are being reviewed in the context of the white community though there were more black respondents<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p334}} than Canadians.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p323}}\n\nOf the white respondents almost 70% were female amidst a community that highly variable and never above 3000 total until the 1940s.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p323}} The proportion of males decreased most of the decades since the religion was established in America. Whites in the community by then were most underrepresented relative to the population at large among those younger than the group 35-40 years old.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp324-6}} The percentage of males peaked around age 45-54 and females had a broad flat high from 40 to 65 - so that the proportion of Bah\u00e1'\u00ed women per age group increased until very late in age - 70 and above. That peak was at a rate around 45 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds per million. The rate of Baha\u2019i membership compared to the national population about matches the mean population age at about near age 45 combining men and women.\n\nHampson observed the overall structure of the age profile of the respondents was natural from increasing age once declared.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p327}} He compared the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed population by age with a simple model from which he made some conclusions:<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp331-2}} there is a broadly near linear increase percentage of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in a rising age range among those still in the religion by 1936 affected only by the overall mortality rate and the overall increase in the size of the whole country, and there was a sharp increase in the adoption of the religion since 1926 and even higher from 1932.\n\nOrientalist scholar E. G. Browne wrote a testimonial obituary for \u2018Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 in January 1922 published in the ''The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland'' wherein he says:<blockquote>One of the most notable practical results of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed ethical teaching in the United States has been, according to the recent testimony of an impartial and qualified observer, the establishment in Bah\u00e1'\u00ed circles in New York of a real fraternity between black and white, and an unprecedented lifting of the \u2018colour bar\u2019, described by the said observer as \u2019almost miraculous\u2019. <ref>{{cite journal\n | author= E. G. Browne\n | author-link = E. G. Browne\n | title = Sir 'Abdu'l-Baha 'Abbas: Died 28th November, 1921\n | journal =The Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland\n | volume =1922\n | issue =1\n | pages =145-146\n | publisher =Cambridge University Press\n | date =Jan 1922\n | url =https://www.jstor.org/stable/25209873?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents\n | jstor =25209873\n | issn =0035-869X\n | oclc= 5543871171\n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref></blockquote> An antagonistic attention against this engagement of the religion is to be found. A KKK newspaper<ref>{{cite book|editor1=David J. Bodenhamer|editor2=Robert G. Barrows|title=The Encyclopedia of Indianapolis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bg13QcMSsq8C|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bg13QcMSsq8C&pg=PA566|chapter=The Fiery Cross |author=Patricia Fogleman|date=22 November 1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-11249-4|page=566}}</ref> ''[[The_Fiery_Cross_(newsletter)|The Fiery Cross]]'' had an entry against the \"Bahaists and Babist\" in New York.<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Heathenism within our borders\n | newspaper =The Fiery Cross\n | location =Indianapolis, IN |editor= Ernest W Reichard| volume=2|number=9\n | page =4\n | date =Feb 2, 1923\n | url =http://bl-libg-doghill.ads.iu.edu/gpd-web/fierycross/192322/192322.pdf \n | access-date = Feb 15, 2020}}</ref> On the other hand a 1925 brief profile of the religion in the African-American newspaper the ''New York Age'' sums it up: \u201cThat is quite a volume of advanced beliefs to introduce in one movement.\"<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Among the imported cults which has found lodgment in this country\u2026\n | newspaper =The New York Age\n | location =New York NY\n | page =7\n | date =26 September 1925\n | url =http://www.newspapers.com/clip/269138/profile_of_bahai_faith_from_holding_a/ \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> In 1927 note was taken of the election of [[Louis Gregory]] echoing coverage in ''The Washington Sentinel'' on the election of Gregory exemplifying the \"spirit of racial amity\" at the 19th convention electing the National Spiritual Assembly.<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Comments by the Age Editors on sayings of other editors\n | newspaper =The New York Age\n | location =New York, NY\n | page =4\n | date =23 July 1927\n | url =http://www.newspapers.com/clip/269247/the_new_york_age/ \n | access-date = Feb 15, 2020}}</ref> Despite all this no significant growth in the black community arose in New York by 1936 according to the Survey.<ref name=StockmanThD/>\n\nHampson found that the whites were mostly Anglo-Saxon/British and almost completely that group plus the northern European (German/Scandinavian) with only a very small percent eastern or southern European though this approximates the general population well.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp335-7}} Among the whites the suggestion from Hampson is that the background affecting attraction to the religion was not their ethnic heritage but one of previous religious experience.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p338}}\n\n=== Religious motivations and characterization===\nMost white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds of the time were elderly white women of British background who had been Unitarian/Universalist or at least one of the liberal denominations (Episcopal and Congregational) of Christianity.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp344-5}} The Unitarian/Universalist position is nominally closer to the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed position on the Christian idea of the trinity as well as the importance of a reasoned faith compared to dogma or church authority.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp342-3}} \n\nSmith proposed the members of the religious sub-groups were underreported into the mainstream groups for the Survey and by relying on anecdotal mention of various individual Bah\u00e1'\u00eds discerned some subgroups may have been important - millenaries<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p155}} (especially Adventism<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p156}}), metaphysical esotericism and quest (especially the search going through Christian Science, New Thought and Theosophy,)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp162-3}}), religious liberalism(its inclusiveness,)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p171}} having a sense of a need for social reconstruction,<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p179}} and personal attachment to 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 (usually as the presence of the Christ spirit or more<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp182-3}} which transformed into an appreciation of the Covenant<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p179}}.) \n\nSmith supported the millenaries group by anecdotally referring to several individuals, publications, and Greenacre reports and the advent issues featured in discussions of 1914 and 1917 though not generally circulated.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp156-7}} Many presentations limited the unveiling of the ideas of [[End time]] era with the quick arrival at its conclusion without \"apocalyptic horrors\u201d but was referenced in 1914, linked with the Christian Era year 70 and destruction of Jerusalem and the Temple with the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Era 70( which was in 1914.)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p158}} This was added to with optimism that peace would be the natural consequence of the war period and according to one report was the key discussion of the national convention.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p159}} Smith described the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed sense of millenarianism as more on the side of post-millenarianism theology, looking for a present active reconstruction of society, and that Bah\u00e1'\u00eds definitely had some [[Adventism]] mixed in as well.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p160}}\n\nFor the metaphysical movement being an appreciable part of the religious background of the white Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, especially New Thought and Theosophy - following a religious search often away from the mainstreams<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p161}} - Smith observed that during 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1\u2019s tour in America in general and at Greenacre featured meetings with such groups, and the presence of Bah\u00e1'\u00ed membership in the Chicago New Thought Executive Committee.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp162-3}} But this group also had a strain with the anti-individualistic approach to the religious priority of its leadership before 1919,<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p164}} and led to an ambivalent co-existent relationship until there were greater tensions later.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p165}} There were new patterns of authority sanctioned while old methods of authority were rejected. Tolerance for non-scriptural practices was allowed but not endorsed albeit some were opposed like the belief in reincarnation. Some of these beliefs that were specifically opposed continued anyway but opposition to claims of personal authority was a greater issue - there were claims of individual conscience and special powers.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p167}} However no process of these claims led to recognized authority in the religion though sometimes lasting or widespread recognition did exist and did lead to cliques and confusions.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p168}} Secret meeting circles occurred which may have been largest in the case of W. H. Harmon who personally revered 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 and associated with the community and teachings but did not join the community. This led to the Committee of Inquiry of 1917-1918,<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p170}} (aka Reading Room Affair.)<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p189}} The group calling itself the Reading Room, avowing Harmon's personal authority, sent delegates to national convention and was challenged by Chicago House of Spirituality in Boston in 1917 - the findings of a committee were supported by attendees of 19 communities followed by essays about the affair in 1918.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp189-90}} Criticisms included they were leading people astray who used occult pretensions to seek money. The 1918 convention was meticulously reviewed for delegate credentials and the convention approved the committee's findings.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp190-1}}\n\nSmith characterized the religious liberalism component of the white population's religious background as having arose out of protestant transformation toward social Christianity between the Civil War and WWI and it was itself opposed by a rise of fundamentalism.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p170}} The liberalism motivations made repeated statements of inclusiveness of ideas, to add to one\u2019s belief from other places, other religions, an approach of being \u201cleaven rather than a cult\u201d and a challenge \"to be more true to what is deepest in their faith\u201d<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp171-2}} while upholding the singular authority of Bah\u00e1\u2019u\u2019ll\u00e1h followed by 'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 and not break ties with previous religious affiliations and even used their presence in them to present Bah\u00e1'\u00ed ideas to them.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p173}} The ambiguous liberalism had strains in relation to the Faith being a distinct set of principles.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p174}} The liberalism emphasized a \u201clive the life\u201d pattern of action and sometimes as collective action. Smith notes peace organizations and race issues seeming to be the broadest efforts associated with this mindset of previous thinking and many audiences occurred of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 and Bah\u00e1'\u00eds with organizations of like mind:<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p175}} NAACP, Bowery Mission, Jane Addams Hull House but also volunteers to the League of Nations to enforce peace though how to proceed was not agreed.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p177}} \n\n'Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1\u2019s personal standing among many was combined with his personal style of tolerance and gradualism though this leveraged peaceable if opposition to existing worldly authority.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p181}} In Britain the appreciation of 'Abdu'l-Bah\u00e1 was less of a high station <ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p182}} and the Americans offended the Londoners with their acts of personal devotion.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|pp181-2}} Nevertheless the primacy of `Abdu\u2019l-Bah\u00e1 of whatever appreciation was a unifying factor in the American Bah\u00e1'\u00ed experience and rose in time in the form of an understanding of the [[Lesser Covenant]] against the challenges of other points of view.<ref name=SmithStudiesv1/>{{rp|p183}}\n\n==After 1936==\nDuring the first Seven Year Plan, 1936-1944, 153 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds moved among the goal areas in America that succeeded in electing assemblies - an average of 6 per goal area.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp269-70}} A few local residents must have joined in - and in some areas more and in some areas less.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p270}} An additional 10 moved to areas that did not elect an assembly by 1944, another 42 moved to areas in Canada and Alaska and 24 moved to areas that became jeopardized. Altogether 248 moved - 10% of the community for the domestic goals alone. There was also an international goal was one assembly per country of the Western Hemisphere.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p270}} In addition to intranational pioneers, at least some 28 pioneers and more than 30 traveling Bah\u00e1'\u00eds registered their trips for the religion set off to 19 Latin American countries.<ref>* {{cite book\n| author=Louie A. Mathews\n | title =The Baha'i Centenary 1844-1944\n | publisher =National Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of the United States |chapter= Baha'i teaching in Latin America to 1940\n | date =1944\n | location =Wilmette, IL\n | pages =195-200\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File%3ACentenary-1844-1944.pdf |chapter-url=https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Centenary-1844-1944.pdf&page=216 \n | oclc= 270631500}}\n* {{cite book\n | author=Artemus Lamb\n | title =The Beginnings of the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in Latin America: Some Remembrances |chapter=First pioneers, believers, and assemblies in each country\n | publisher =VanOrman Enterprises\n | edition =English Revised and Amplified\n | date =  November 1995\n | location =San Salvador\n | language =Spanish\n | url =https://bahai-library.com/lamb_bahai_latin_america |chapter-url=https://bahai-library.com/lamb_bahai_latin_america#7}}</ref> Hampson observed a significant effect internationally was the role of individuals as well.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p358}} \n\nA few individuals have been found noteworthy in raising up communities in the country.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Women in the North American Baha'i Community |author1=Sandra Hutchinson |author2= Richard Hollinger| editor= Rosemary Skinner Keller |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of women and religion in North America |volume= 2 |year= 2006 |publisher=Indiana Univ. Press |location=Bloomington, IN |isbn= 9780253346858 | oclc= 836273399 |page= 779 }}</ref> Three ladies were noted who \"single-handedly\" established new communities by giving public lectures on then-popular topics and then inviting people to attend a series of classes on the religion. The number of local assemblies in America doubled from 1937 to 1945.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p364}} Another factor was in the size which continued to be a key dynamic of the community - a tendency to encourage Bah\u00e1'\u00eds to spread out to form more communities rather than larger communities once it reached about 15 adult active members of the community which has been documented from the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news\n | title =Goals for this Baha'i Year\n | newspaper =Baha'i News\n | page =5\n | date =May 1948 |number=207\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Baha%27i_News_207.pdf&page=5 \n | access-date = }}</ref> The average size of the community with assemblies in 1936 was 30 adults which dropped to 15 in 1947 and 14.2 in 1991; 15 was seen as ideal community size after 1936 and there was encouragement to spread out at that point and to go to small towns after 1976.<ref name=Holinger>{{cite book\n | author= Richard Hollinger\n | title =Community Histories |chapter=Introduction\n | publisher = Kailmat Press\n | series =Studies in the Babi and Baha\u2019i Religions\n | volume =6 |editor1= Richard Hollinger |editor2= series editor Anthony A. Lee\n | date =1992\n | location =Los Angeles, CA\n | pages = xxix, xxx, xxxiv, xxxix\n | oclc=32305770\n | isbn = 9780933770768 }}</ref> In the winter of 1952-3 the Guardian said to disperse even for the largest communities,<ref>{{cite news\n | title =On the character and purpose of the world crusade; Jubilee Celebration |author=Ruhiyyih Khanum\n | newspaper =Baha'i News\n | page =22\n | date =May 6, 1953\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Jubilee_Celebration_1953.pdf&page=22 \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> and on 28 May 1953 called for dispersal of pioneers to virgin areas and continued in later years.<ref>* {{cite book\n | author=Lewis Ware\n | title =Baha'i World |chapter=In memoriam; Elizabeth S. Laws, 1888-1977, Knight of Baha'u'llah\n | publisher =Universal House of Justice\n | series =An International Record\n | volume =17\n | date =1981\n | location =Haifa, Israel\n | page =459\n | url = https://bahai.works/Bah\u00e1\u2019%C3%AD_World/Volume_17 |chapter-url=https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:BW_Volume17.pdf&page=479 \n | isbn = 9780853981305\n |oclc= 461956705 }}\n* {{cite news\n | title =National Spiritual Assembly; The home front teaching plan; The Role of Assemblies\n | newspaper = Baha'i News\n | page =6\n | date = Jun 1954\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Baha%27i_News_280.pdf&page=6 \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}\n* {{cite news\n | title =All-Alaska teaching conference\n | newspaper =Baha'i News\n | page =7\n | date =Oct 1955 |number=296\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:Baha%27i_News_296.pdf&page=7 \n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}\n* {{cite news\n | title = The Guardian called for dispersal on the home front\n | newspaper = US Supplement to the Baha'i News\n | page =2\n | date =October 1962\n | url =https://bahai.works/index.php?title=File:US_Supplement_56.pdf&page=2\n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> In the 1960s the act of local incorporation was suggested for a community with a minimum of 15 adults,<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Letter from the National Spiritual Assembly\n | newspaper =US Supplement to the Baha'i News\n | page =1\n | date =Aug 1965\n | url =https://bahai.works/File:US_Supplement_90.pdf\n | access-date =Feb 15, 2020 }}</ref> and individuals living in communities with more than 15 were asked to spread out to sustain spiritual assemblies.<ref>{{cite book |author=Mike McMullen |title=The Bah\u00e1\u02bc\u00eds of America: The Growth of a Religious Movement |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iecWCgAAQBAJ |date=27 November 2015 |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-1-4798-5152-2 |oclc= 1136454836 |page=133}}</ref>\n\n==Opposition and opportunity==\nHampson observed most of the spread of the Faith over the long term has followed the three variables: higher area basic population, socio-economic dynamism, and highway penetration.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p305}} He noticed an oppositional area however - that by 1980 \u201cBaha\u2019is fail to be present where one might expect \u2026throughout a very large wedge that extends eastward (from the Great Plains) and gradually curls around the southern portions of Illinois, Indiana, and Ohio, terminating [into] the southern flank of Pennsylvania [and a] tiny prong \u2026 reaches the Atlantic via southern Virginia.\u201d<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p298}} Hampson doesn\u2019t name this region but much of it is pretty much the middle and northern [[Confederate_States_of_America#Span_of_control|span of control of the Confederacy]] when it isn\u2019t an urban center. Some of this region fits the lack of dynamism and highway accessibility but not enough to explain the overall relative gap in Hampson's estimation.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp297-8}}\n\nThis is contrasted with the unusual acceptance of the religion, in Hampson's analysis, along the northern regions of the Union especially along the Canadian border and then along the Gulf and southeast coast, to favoring the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds, which Hampson speculates might be due to the Bah\u00e1'\u00eds reaching out to the black community,<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p300}} which he notes more clearly since 1954.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p315}} The region of resistance is also cut by some growth along the highways and towards larger urbanized areas from Chicago and the states near and west of Chicago (Illinois, Wisconsin, Minnesota, Iowa and Missouri),<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp312-3}} and in mid-Atlantic part of the South - Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina into South Carolina and Georgia which was largely more urbanized in larger population centers.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp314-5}}\n\nBah\u00e1'\u00eds were more concentrated in larger cities before 1936 and this was cut to less than half by 1976.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp312-3}} Circa 1976 Bah\u00e1'\u00eds favored towns up to 45000 people even above that of the national population and lived in major cities at the lowest rate.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|pp308-9}} At the rate per million of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds in the modern era, on average a town or county area of about 45000 people has enough people to form an assembly whereas larger cities with larger numbers of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds could have larger numbers leave and not affect assembly status.<ref name=HampsonPhD/>{{rp|p311}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Smkolins", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bah%C3%A1%27%C3%AD_Historical_Record_Survey"}
