" valign=\"bottom\" | Saskatchewan\n| align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | 11.46\n| align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | 17.83\n| align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | 5.19\n|- \n| height=\"11\" align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | Yukon\n| align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | 15.30\n| align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | 26.84\n| align=\"right\" valign=\"bottom\" | 3.91\n|}\n\nSource:<ref name=\"statscan1\">[[Statistics Canada]]. CANSIM Table 102-0563. ''Leading causes of death, total population, by sex, Canada, provinces and territories, annual''.</ref>\n\nCanada's regional rate of 71.0 in Nunavut would place Nunavut second highest in the world{{when?|date=October 2019}} if it were a country.<ref>[[List of countries by suicide rate]]</ref> In 2019, it was reported to be the highest in the world.<ref>https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2019/10/10/inuit-highest-suicide-rate</ref>\n\nWith 86.5 suicides per 100,000 population in 2006, males' rates over the age of 74 in the [[Russian Federation]] exceed by threefold Canadian males' rate among the same age cohort, however Canada's Nunavut males of all ages exceeded the elderly Russian male rate by thirty per cent.<ref>World Health Organization, ''WHO: Suicide rates'', http://www.who.int/entity/mental_health/media/russ.pdf (Accessed August 22, 2011).</ref> During 2000\u20132007, there were between 13 and 25 male suicides recorded annually in the Nunavut territory, accounting for between 16% and 30% of total annual mortality.<ref name=\"statscan1\" />\n\n=== By age group ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" generated with [[:de:Wikipedia:Helferlein/VBA-Macro for EXCEL tableconversion]] V1.8<\\hiddentext>\n|+ Rate of suicide, all Canadians, average over 2000\u20132007, according to age at death<br />''Age-standardized mortality rate per 100,000 population''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Both sexes\n! scope=\"col\" | Males\n! scope=\"col\" | Females\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold\" height=\"11\" valign=\"bottom\" | All a